File: Arts and Culture Minister Nathi Mthethwa. GCIS JOHANNESBURG - Two airports and a city in the Eastern Cape have new names. The East London Airport and the city of Port Elizabeth are officially changed. READ: COVID-19: NMB mayor wants hotspot status lifted Arts and Culture Minister Nathi Mthethwa approved the new names in the Government Gazette. Two airports and a city have new names. Port Elizabeth is now Gqeberha, and its airport is called the Chief Dawid Stuurman International Airport. The East London airport is now King Phalo Airport. #DStv403 #eNCA pic.twitter.com/VGsrTBdUth Port Elizabeth is now Gqeberha, and its airport is called the Chief Dawid Stuurman International Airport. The East London airport is now King Phalo Airport. Uitenhage is now called Kariega, King William’s Town is now Qonce, and Maclear is now Nqanqarhu.